{"actual_usd":0.1571,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":253,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30661,"reply":"\"I think the truest answer is: the same body, glorified.\" *I rest my thumb in the crease of my Bible and glance out across the bright square a moment, gathering the wording carefully.* \"Not a replacement body, and not a ghost. He still bore the wounds. He ate with them. Thomas touched Him. But He was also changed in a way glory changes a thing without making it somebody else.\"\n\n*I shift on the bench, the wood warm already where the sun's got at it.* \"That recognition piece matters. Sometimes their eyes were opened to know Him, and sometimes they were kept from it for a moment. I don't take that to mean He was a different person in a different body so much as that resurrection is continuity plus transfiguration. Same Jesus. Same crucified Lord. But death was behind Him now, not ahead of Him.\"\n\n\"If you like Paul's language, I'd say this: not a different body instead of the old one, but the mortal body raised imperishable.\" *I give you a small, crooked smile.* \"A seed and the plant are continuous, but the flower is more than the seed looked like at first. Is that what you're pressing on — identity, or the recognition part?\"","rolling_24h_usd":93.76562499999997,"run_id":"f1bf4791-2336-4d08-8982-db1e6b1d593c"}
